A framework for building a story from personal experience outward to full dramatic structure.

Steps 1–7 generate the **ingredients**. Step 8 is the **container** (plot structure) that holds them. Step 9 is permission to break the container once you understand it.

## How the steps map onto plot structure

| Nelson's step | Where it lives in the arc |
|---|---|
| Step 1 — personal experience | Exposition — the emotional core of the story |
| Step 2 — different POV | Shapes the narrative voice throughout the entire arc |
| Step 3 — ticking clock | Drives rising action, sets the climax deadline |
| Step 4 — props / objects | Planted in exposition, paid off at climax or resolution |
| Step 5 — transitional situation | Plot Turn 1 (inciting incident) and Plot Turn 2 (climax) |
| Step 6 — world event | Backdrop that pressures the rising action |
| Step 7 — binary forces | Engine of conflict across the entire arc |
| Step 8 — Freytag / 7-point | The container that organises everything above |
| Step 9 — experiment | Where you break the container deliberately |

**Practical workflow:**
1. Use steps 1–7 to generate raw material and devices
2. Use step 8 to decide where each element lands in the arc
3. Use step 9 to decide which rules to break once you understand them

